Here's a C++ function that takes a reference to a std::string containing markdown formatted text and returns a std::string containing HTML formatted text:
```cpp
#include <string>
#include <regex>
#include <iostream>

std::string markdownToHtml(const std::string& markdown) {
    std::string html = markdown;

    // Convert headings
    std::regex headingRegex("#+(\\s*)(.*)");
    std::regex_replace(std::back_inserter(html), html.begin(), html.end(), headingRegex, "<h1>\\2</h1>");
    std.regex_replace(std.back_inserter(html), html.begin(), html.end(), std.regex("#+(\\s)"), "</h1><h2>");
    std.regex_replace(std.back_inserter(html), html.begin(), html.end(), std.regex("(?<=</h2>)#+(\\s)"), "</h2>");

    // Convert lists
    std.regex listRegex("(\\*|\\d+\\.)\\s*(.*)");
    std.regex_replace(std.back_inserter(html), html.begin(), html.end(), listRegex, "<li>\\3</li>");
    std.regex_replace(std.back_inserter(html), html.begin(), html.end(), std.regex("(?<=</li>)(\\*|\\d+\\.)"), "</li><li>");

    // Convert links
    std.regex linkRegex("\\[(.*)\\]\\((.*)");
    std.regex_replace(std.back_inserter(html), html.begin(), html.end(), linkRegex, "<a href=\"\\2\">\\1</a>");

    // Convert bold and italic text
    std.regex boldItalicRegex("\\*(.*)\\*\\*(.*)\\*");
    std.regex_replace(std.back_inserter(html), html.begin(), html.end(), boldItalicRegex, "<strong><i>\\1</i></strong>");
    std.regex boldRegex("\\*(.*)\\*");
    std.regex_replace(std.back_inserter(html), html.begin(), html.end(), boldRegex, "<strong>\\1</strong>");
    std.regex italicRegex("\\*(.*)\\*");
    std.regex_replace(std.back_inserter(html), html.begin(), html.end(), italicRegex, "<i>\\1</i>");

    return html;
}
```
In this function, we use regular expressions to replace markdown formatting with HTML formatting. The function uses `std::regex` and `std::regex_replace` to make the replacements.

The function first converts headings by replacing `#` with `h1`, `h2`, etc. It then converts lists by replacing bullet points and numbers with `<li>` elements. Next, it converts links by replacing `[...]` with `<a>` elements. Finally, it converts bold and italic text by replacing asterisks with `strong` and `emphasis` elements.

Note that this function is not a complete markdown to HTML converter, and it might not handle all possible markdown formatting. However, it should handle the most common ones.

